<center>
<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="10" width=70%>
<tr>
<td>
<span style="color:rgb(0, 0, 0);font-family:helvetica;font-size:12pt">
My primary research goal is to measure the CMB polarization, witch the hope of detecting what is know as the "B-mode" signal in the pattern of polarization vectors on the sky. We have fielded a microwave polarimeter known as the Keck Array at the South Pole. To the left you can see an image of the Temperature anisotropies in the CMB taken in ~40hrs during the 2012 season.<br>
<p>
For more information, you can look through a <a href="physics/SCAR_tolan.pdf">talk about the Keck Array</a> I recently gave.<br>
<p>
</td>

<td><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
 <tr><td>
<img alt="cmbT" src="physics/cmb2012_less_contrast.png" width=400>

<p>
<small style="font-style: italic;"><small><span style="color: rgb(255, 255, 255);"> CMB Temperature with the Keck Array</span></small></small><p>
</span>

</td></tr></table>
</td>
</tr>



<tr>
<td>
<span style="color:rgb(0, 0, 0);font-family:helvetica;font-size:12pt">
The Keck Array deployed to the South Pole in November 2010, and achieved first light in February 2011.
<p>


<p>
</td>

<td><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
 <tr><td>
<img alt="cmbT" src="physics/5keck.png" width=250>

<p>
<small style="font-style: italic;"><small><span style="color: rgb(255, 255, 255);"> The Keck Array at the South Pole</span></small></small><p>
</span>

</td></tr></table>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
<span style="color:rgb(0, 0, 0);font-family:helvetica;font-size:12pt">
A map of polarized sky can be decomposed into two components: one with gradient and no curl, the "E-modes," and one with curl and no gradient, the "B-modes." On a sphere, this decomposition is complete, however in a cut sky map, we must be carefully handle "ambiguous modes," which occur because of the boundary conditions. These ambiguous modes are also created by data processing artifacts in the maps that all real experiments create. One the left you can see a selection of the largest eigenvalue modes of "E-modes" for a small patch of sky. 
<p>


<p>
</td>

<td><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
